<section xml:id="sec-preimages" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Pre-Images</title>

  <p> For a function <m>f:D \to \R</m> and a subset <m>A</m> of <m>\R</m>, the 
    <alert>pre-image of <m>A</m> under <m>f</m></alert> is the set of all inputs whose image belongs 
    to <m>A</m>; in notation, <m>f^{-1}(A)=\{x \in D: f(x)\in A\}</m>. Consider the example <m>f(x)=x^2</m> 
    and <m>A=[2,4)</m>. We want to determine all values of <m>x</m> for which <m>x^2 \in [2,4)</m>, and we 
    can do this analytically. If <m>2 \le x^2 \lt 4</m>, then either <m>\sqrt{2} \le x \lt 2</m> or 
    <m>-2 \lt x \le - \sqrt{2}</m>; hence <m>f^{-1}(A)=(-2,-\sqrt{2}] \cup [\sqrt{2},2)</m>. Graphically, any 
    point <m>(x,f(x))</m> on the graph of <m>f</m> that lies in the horizontal strip <m>2 \le y \lt 4</m> 
    yields a value of <m>x</m> for which <m>2 \le f(x) \lt 4</m>.
  </p>

